04082nam a22006495i 9781501733376DE-B159720191126113341.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||191126s2019    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017333767 a10.7591/97815017333762doi  a(DE-B1597)533830  a(OCoLC)1129181180  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aLIT0000002bisacsh1 aBellamy, Elizabeth J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTranslations of Power :bNarcissim and the Unconscious in Epic History /cElizabeth J. Bellamy. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2019] 4cÂ©1992  a1 online resource (280 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tCHAPTER ONE. Psychoanalyzing Epic History -- tCHAPTER TWO. A Disturbance of Memory in Carthage -- tCHAPTER THREE. Habendi Libido: Ariosto's Armor of Narcissism -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Troia Vittrice: Reviving Troy in the Woods of Jerusalem -- tCHAPTER FIVE. The Alienating Structure of Prophecy in "Faerie Lond" -- tCHAPTER SIX. Obsessional Time: Waiting for Death in Epic -- tFrequently Cited Secondary Sources -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aElizabeth J. Bellamy here casts new theoretical light on the Renaissance genre of the dynastic epic. Drawing upon Freudian and Lacanian psychoanalysis to illuminate the emergence of an epic "subjecthood," she focuses on Virgil's Aeneid, Ariosto's Orlando furioso, Tasso's Gerusalemme liberata, and Spenser's Faerie Queene in an attempt to demonstrate how the operations of the unconscious may be interpreted within narrative history.Bellamy first evaluates the psychoanalytic approach to epic as a possible alternative to the new historicism. Turning to the Aeneid, she discusses Freud's'neurotic'relation to Rome as a founding image for a historical unconscious. She then interweaves a genealogy of epic subjecthood with the motif of the translatio imperii, likening the'translations of power'that constitute the translatio imperii to extended meditations on the fate of Troy throughout literary history. According to Bellamy, the epic genre manifests a repeated displacement and repression of its Trojan origins, and the doomed city of Troy represents the locus of epic's own narrative narcissism. Offering provocative analyses of epic temporality and of the function of the death drive in epic narrative, she concludes that dynastic epic may be seen as a structure of narcissistic desire which undermines the capacity of the epic to embody a fully articulated historical subject.Translations of Power will enliven current debates among scholars and students of Renaissance culture, literary theory, gender studies, and psychoanalytic criticism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh40uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/9781501733376423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501733376.jpg  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LT  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LT  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG